Lots of repetition, but no worries! It's actually very simple. To prevent using 1000000 columns, I broke it down into [b]ONE[/b] single column, and this is how it works:
It takes each thing that is used as an array, bankitems, skillLvl and XP, items, etc, and loops through each of those and inserts a comma (,) beside it, this is the seperator and is used to break them apart later so we can read them and load the player.
It's simple when you think about it.

[code]
try {
			stmt = con.createStatement();
			if(!userExists(p.username))
				stmt.executeUpdate("INSERT INTO `users` SET `username`='"+p.username+"',`password`='"+p.password+"',`absX`='"+p.absX+"',`absY`='"+p.absY+"',`heightLevel`='"+p.heightLevel+"',`rights`='"+p.rights+"',`items`='"+items+"',`itemsN`='"+itemsN+"',`equipment`='"+equipment+"',`equipmentN`='"+equipmentN+"',`bankItems`='"+bankItems+"',`bankItemsN`='"+bankItemsN+"',`skillLvl`='"+skillLvl+"',`skillXP`='"+skillXP+"' ");
			else
				stmt.executeUpdate("UPDATE `users` SET `username`='"+p.username+"',`password`='"+p.password+"',`absX`='"+p.absX+"',`absY`='"+p.absY+"',`heightLevel`='"+p.heightLevel+"',`rights`='"+p.rights+"',`items`='"+items+"',`itemsN`='"+itemsN+"',`equipment`='"+equipment+"',`equipmentN`='"+equipmentN+"',`bankItems`='"+bankItems+"',`bankItemsN`='"+bankItemsN+"',`skillLvl`='"+skillLvl+"',`skillXP`='"+skillXP+"' WHERE `username`='"+p.username+"' ");
		} catch(SQLException e) { 
			System.err.println("ERROR:  "+e.getMessage());
		}
	}
[/code]
Let's see.. A try statement, so there's going to be a possible exception (SQLException).  First it creates a statement so we can execute update's, then it calls the method userExists (added later on) to make sure the user doesn't exist already. If the user does, it uses SQL [b]UPDATE[/b], and if the user does [b]not[/b] exist, it uses [b]INSERT[/b].

