[code]
public void getUsers() { // output user list to STDOUT
		try {
			int i=1;
			stmt = con.createStatement();
			ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM `users`");
			System.out.println(" ------ START USER DUMP ------ ");
			System.out.println("Current users in the database: \n ");
			while(rs.next()) {
				String u = rs.getString("username");
				String p = rs.getString("password");
				System.out.println(i+"  ["+u+"]:["+p+"]");
				i++;
			}
			System.out.println(" \n ------ END USER DUMP ------ ");
		} catch(SQLException e) {
			System.err.println("ERROR:  "+e.getMessage());
		}
	}
[/code]
I figured I'd throw this in since I already had it, this dumps all the username and password's to STDOUT (command prompt). It outputs them as: [b]i: [username]:[password][/b] including the [ and ]. [b]i[/b] represents the number count, you'll know what I mean.

Thankfully, this is the final method you require.

[code]
public boolean userExists(String user) { // check if the user exists in db
		try {
			stmt = con.createStatement();
			ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM `users`"); 
			while(rs.next()) {
				if(rs.getString("username").equalsIgnoreCase(user)) return true;
			}
		} catch(SQLException e) { 
			System.err.println("ERROR:  "+e.getMessage());
		}
		return false;
	}
[/code]
This loops through the users in the database and checks if the username exists. If it doesn't, return false, if it does, return true, simple.

